[0.000, "o", "    # TH (Tyrosine Hydroxylase) — Expert Analysis\r\n    **Biological function.** TH catalyzes the rate-limiting step of catecholamine biosynthesis: hydroxylation of L-tyrosine to L-DOPA using tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4), O₂, and Fe²⁺. L-DOPA is the obligate precursor for dopamine, norepinephrine, and epinephrine. Expression is restricted to catecholaminergic neurons (substantia nigra pars compacta, ventral tegmental area, locus coeruleus), sympathetic ganglia, and adrenal chromaffin cells. The 497-aa enzyme is a homotetramer with an N-terminal regulatory domain (Ser19/Ser31/Ser40 phosphorylation by PKA, CaMKII, ERK1/2 — Ser40 phosphorylation relieves catecholamine feedback inhibition) and a C-terminal catalytic domain harboring the iron-binding 2-His-1-carboxylate facial triad. The 14 transcripts / 8 protein-coding isoforms reflect alternative splicing in exon 1/2 that is human-specific (hTH1–hTH4) and absent in rodents — a frequently overlooked detail that breaks cross-species inference.\r\n    **Key"]
[0.000, "o", " variants.** Biallelic loss-of-function in TH causes **DOPA-responsive dystonia / infantile parkinsonism (Segawa-like, autosomal recessive)** — OMIM 605407. The promoter -71C>T variant (c.-71C>T) is the most common pathogenic allele in European cohorts and produces a mild phenotype rescuable with low-dose L-DOPA. Missense alleles in the catalytic domain (e.g., p.R233H, p.R328W, p.L205P) destabilize the tetramer and produce the severe, encephalopathic phenotype with poor L-DOPA response. The promoter -824T>G polymorphism modulates expression and has been associated with neuropsychiatric phenotypes. Heterozygous carriers are clinically silent — this is a strictly recessive locus, unlike PARK genes.\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    **Disease associations.** Beyond the monogenic syndrome, TH-positive neurons of the SNc are the cells lost in **Parkinson's disease**; TH immunohistochemistry remains the gold-standard readout for nigrostriatal degeneration in both human post-mortem and MPTP/6-OHDA/α-synuclein models. TH activity declines with age and is reduced in PD striatum before frank cell loss, making it a sensitive early biomarker. Catecholamine excess from pheochromocytoma/paraganglioma involves TH-expressing chromaffin tumors (use TH IHC alongside chromogranin A). Don't conflate TH loss with dopaminergic neuron loss — early PD shows TH downregulation in surviving neurons.\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "    **Experimental recommendations.** (1) For expression work, use isoform-resolving assays — RT-qPCR primers spanning the alternative exon 1/2 junctions, or long-read RNA-seq; standard 3'-tag scRNA-seq cannot distinguish hTH1–hTH4. (2) For protein, validate antibody specificity in TH-knockout tissue or with the Pel-Freez sheep polyclonal (AB152) which has the cleanest track record; phospho-specific antibodies (pSer40, pSer31) are essential for activity inference because total TH protein does not equal activity. (3) For functional readout, pair TH IHC/Western with HPLC-ECD measurement of L-DOPA, dopamine, DOPAC, and HVA — TH protein levels routinely dissociate from catecholamine output. (4) For genetic models, the human-specific isoforms make humanized iPSC-derived midbrain organoids or knock-in mice preferable to standard Th⁻/⁻ mice for variant modeling. (5) For CRISPR perturbation, target the catalytic domain (exons 6–11) rather than the alternatively spliced 5' region to ensure pan-isoform knoc"]
[0.000, "o", "kout.\r\n"]
